{"id":"math-ph/0308024","submitter":"Yair Zarmi","authors":"John R. Ockendon Yair Zarmi","title":"Representation of solutions of linear PDE's with constant coefficients\n  as superpositions of solutions in lower dimensions","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math-ph math.AP math.MP","license":null,"abstract":"  A unified approach to the representation of solutions of linear PDE's with\nconstant coefficients in high dimensions in terms of solutions of the same\nPDE's in lower dimensions is presented. It is based on the observation that if\na function of an (N+1)-dimensional variable (N * 2) has a convergent Fourier\nintegral representation, then it may be written as a superposition of rotated\nplane waves in any number of dimensions lower than N+1. If that function is a\nsolution of a linear PDE with constant coefficients, and, in addition, the\nequation is invariant under a spatial group of transformations (e.g.,\nrotations, or Lorentz transformations), then the superposition is in terms of\nsolutions of lower- (not only two-) dimensiuonal solutions of the same PDE. As\nexamples, representations of solutions of the Laplace equation in (N+1)\ndimensions and of the wave equation in (1+N) dimensions (N * 2) as\nsuperpositions of solutions in lower dimensions are discussed, and simple\nconsequences are presented.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 21 Aug 2003 14:49:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
